{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"539"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/539"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.01,0.64,0.1,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114576"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/539"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114576"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing fatigue over several months, worse in the week following her menstrual period. She immigrated from Egypt three years ago. She reports her periods have gradually become heavier, now lasting four days every month. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She eats a balanced diet including meat and vegetables with no dietary restrictions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer full blood examination shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 102 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 75 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell haemoglobin concentration 24 pg (27-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 6.8 x 10^9/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 315 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious blood tests from three years ago showed a haemoglobin greater than 110 g/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalassaemia minor","Carcinoma of the caecum","Abnormal uterine bleeding","Dietary iron deficiency","Hookworm infection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a new microcytic, hypochromic anaemia that has developed over the past three years, with symptoms of fatigue and increasingly heavy menstrual periods. The blood picture is typical of iron deficiency anaemia, with low haemoglobin, reduced mean cell volume (MCV), and low mean cell haemoglobin concentration (MCHC). Any of the listed options could lead to an iron deficiency anaemia which is caused by either inadequate intake of iron, malabsorption of iron, or loss or iron through blood loss or excessive use of iron.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal uterine bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause given her age, gender, and history of worsening menstrual blood loss. Heavy menstrual bleeding is the most common cause of iron deficiency anaemia in women of reproductive age, accounting for up to 80% of cases in this demographic. Her symptoms worsen after menstruation, supporting this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassaemia minor\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely for several reasons. While it can present with a similar blood picture and is more common in Mediterranean populations, it is a genetic condition present from birth. Her previous normal haemoglobin three years ago effectively rules this out. Additionally, thalassaemia typically shows a more marked microcytosis relative to the degree of anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the caecum\u003C/strong\u003E would be very unusual in a 34-year-old woman. While colorectal cancer should be considered in unexplained iron deficiency anaemia, particularly in those over 50, this patient has no red flag symptoms such as weight loss, change in bowel habits, or abdominal pain. However, it is important to be aware that colorectal cancer is now being seen more frequently in younger age groups. The presence of cyclical symptoms related to menstruation points away from a gastrointestinal cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary iron deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given her reported balanced diet including meat and vegetables. Pure dietary iron deficiency is rare in developed countries and usually only occurs with severe dietary restrictions or malnutrition. Even vegetarians usually maintain adequate iron stores through careful dietary choices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHookworm infection\u003C/strong\u003E (usually \u003Cem\u003EAncylostoma duodenale\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ENecator americanus\u003C/em\u003E) can cause iron deficiency through chronic gastrointestinal blood loss. However, after three years in a non-endemic country, any pre-existing infection would likely have resolved. Additionally, hookworm infection typically presents with additional symptoms such as abdominal pain and diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iron deficiency anaemia in women of reproductive age is most commonly due to menstrual blood loss.","A microcytic, hypochromic blood picture with normal white cell and platelet counts suggests iron deficiency.","New onset anaemia requires investigation of the underlying cause, even when a likely explanation exists.","Heavy menstrual bleeding is defined as blood loss greater than 80mL per cycle or periods lasting longer than 7 days that that interferes with physical, emotional, or social well-being."],"references":["Pasricha SR, Flecknoe\u2010Brown SC, Allen KJ, Gibson PR, McMahon LP, Olynyk JK, Roger SD, Savoia HF, Tampi R, Thomson AR, Wood EM. Diagnosis and management of iron deficiency anaemia: a clinical update. Medical Journal of Australia. 2010 Nov;193(9):525-32."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"539"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T16:51:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T16:52:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"539"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114576"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49: